descript.abstract:
Meteorological data are being collected at several points within four intensive study areas in Barrow.  These data assist in the calculation of the energy balance at the land surface and are also useful as inputs into modeling activities. (http://dx.doi.org/10.5440/1164893).&#xD;
&#xD;
Measurements at AREA A (all heights listed are relative to the land surface):&#xD;
Location of the Site A station: N71* 16.888', W156* 36.647'&#xD;
* Air temperature at three heights: 1.4 meters, 2.0 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* Relative Humidity / Dew Point at two heights: 1.4 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* Wind Speed at two heights: 1.3 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* 4 Component Net Radiation @ 1.2 meters&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Shortwave Radiation&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Longwave Radiation&#xD;
* Summer Precipitation&#xD;
Site A is located on polygonal permafrost and co-located with continuous snow depth measurements and subsurface measurements.&#xD;
&#xD;
Measurements at AREA B (all heights listed are relative to the land surface):&#xD;
Location of the Site B station: N71* 16.785', W156* 36.211'&#xD;
* Air temperature at three heights: 1.4 meters, 2.0 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* Relative Humidity / Dew Point at two heights: 1.4 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* Wind Speed at two heights: 1.3 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* 4 Component Net Radiation @ 1.2 meters&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Shortwave Radiation&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Longwave Radiation&#xD;
* Summer Precipitation&#xD;
Site B is located on polygonal permafrost and co-located with continuous snow depth measurements and subsurface measurements.&#xD;
-------------------------------------------------&#xD;
&#xD;
Measurements at AREA  C (all heights listed are relative to the land surface):&#xD;
Location of the Site C station: N71* 16.804', W156* 36.072'&#xD;
* Air temperature at three heights: 1.4 meters, 2.0 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* Relative Humidity / Dew Point at two heights: 1.4 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* Wind Speed at two heights: 1.3 meters, 3.5 meters&#xD;
* 4 Component Net Radiation @ 1.2 meters&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Shortwave Radiation&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Longwave Radiation&#xD;
* Summer Precipitation&#xD;
* Barometric Pressure&#xD;
Site C is located on polygonal permafrost and co-located with continuous snow depth measurements and subsurface measurements.&#xD;
-------------------------------------------------&#xD;
&#xD;
Measurements at AREA  D (all heights listed are relative to the land surface):&#xD;
Location of the Site D station: N71* 16.927', W156* 36.036'&#xD;
* Air temperature at one height: 1.2 meters&#xD;
* Relative Humidity / Dew Point at one height: 1.2&#xD;
* Wind Speed at one height: 1.2 meters&#xD;
* 4 Component Net Radiation @ 1.0 meters&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Shortwave Radiation&#xD;
** Upwelling & Downwelling Longwave Radiation&#xD;
Site D is located on polygonal permafrost and co-located with continuous snow depth measurements and subsurface measurements.&#xD;
&#xD;
Data are in ASCII files, with columns separated by commas: ','

method.methdesc:
Data is processed internally using a data quality and management suite of tools.  Site is installed following WMO protocol as appropriate.  &#xD;
&#xD;
References:&#xD;
Quantity is Nothing without Quality: Automated QA/QC for Streaming Environmental Sensor Data. John L. Campbell, Lindsey E. Rustad, John H. Porter, Jeffrey R. Taylor, Ethan W. Dereszynski, James B. Shanley, Corinna Gries, Donald L. Henshaw, Mary E. Martin, Wade M. Sheldon, and Emery R. Boose. BioScience2013 63 (7), 574-585 [http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1525/bio.2013.63.7.10] [doi: http://dx.doi.org/10.1525/bio.2013.63.7.10]&#xD;
&#xD;
Measurement and Reporting Practices for Automatic Agricultural Weather Stations. American Society of Agricultural and Biological Engineers. (ASAE) EP505 April 2004. [http://texaset.tamu.edu/documents/ASABE%20Standard.pdf]&#xD;
&#xD;
Guide to Meteorological Instruments and Methods of Observation. World Meteorological Organization (WMO)-No. 8. 2008. ISBN 978-92-63-10008-5. [https://www.wmo.int/pages/prog/gcos/documents/gruanmanuals/CIMO/CIMO_Guide-7th_Edition-2008.pdf]&#xD;
&#xD;
Current configuration of US Climate Reference Network Stations. T. P. Meyers, M. E. Hall, C. B. Baker, R. P. Hosker, Jr., J. A. Jensen, M. R. Helfert, M. T. Young. [http://www1.ncdc.noaa.gov/pub/data/uscrn/documentation/research/CurrentConfigUSCRN-AMSmtg-Jan04-final.pdf]&#xD;
&#xD;
Quality Assurance: Station is visited several times over summer season and at least once per winter. Desiccant is replaced twice per year in the radiometers and main instrument box.  Sensors are checked for levelness, environmental detritus, corrosion, another anomalies that can be visually inspected during these visits.&#xD;
Quality Checking: Since there is some duplication across the BEO, spatial comparisons of all parameters are possible.  This is done in an automated fashion using internal tools as well as through manual observation on the 2-week to monthly time scale.  Radiation data is also compared with data from the ARM facility.  Summer precipitation is also compared with data from the NOAA CRN facility.

ome.datause:
Data are contained in individual ASCII format text files.&#xD;
Lines 1 - 4: Header describing the site & data&#xD;
Lines 6 to N: Column 1 = Timestep in YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS format; Column 2 = data element&#xD;
